00:13.547 --> 00:16.117
Chances are you haven't
been to this place.

00:18.886 --> 00:21.689
Chances are this is a
place you've never seen,

00:24.925 --> 00:28.061
other than maybe blurry
cell phone videos,

00:28.062 --> 00:31.365
old black-and-white newsreels
from World War II.

00:32.433 --> 00:33.800
Chances are bad things were

00:33.801 --> 00:38.738
happening in the
footage you saw.

00:38.739 --> 00:41.641
Myanmar: after 50
years of nightmare,

00:41.642 --> 00:44.244
something unexpected
is happening here.

00:44.245 --> 00:45.779
And it's pretty incredible.

01:30.691 --> 01:33.793
In Yangon, capital city
of Myanmar, it's dark.

01:33.794 --> 01:37.631
Blackouts are frequent with
the ancient power grid.

01:41.969 --> 01:43.303
What sources of light there are

01:43.304 --> 01:47.740
in the street cast an
eerie, yellow/orange hue.

01:47.741 --> 01:50.310
For almost 100 years
under British rule,

01:50.311 --> 01:51.978
this was Rangoon.

01:51.979 --> 01:53.680
In 1948, after helping the

01:53.681 --> 01:55.682
British fight off the Japanese,

01:55.683 --> 01:57.650
and with a new taste for
self-determination, the

01:57.651 --> 02:00.188
country gained independence.

02:04.692 --> 02:06.826
After a decade of
instability, however,

02:06.827 --> 02:11.231
the military consolidated
power and never let go.

02:11.232 --> 02:12.332
Elections?

02:12.333 --> 02:13.833
They came and went.

02:13.834 --> 02:16.569
The results ignored,
opposition punished

02:16.570 --> 02:19.372
or silenced entirely.

02:19.373 --> 02:22.209
Burma, now Myanmar, where
Orwell had once served

02:22.210 --> 02:25.178
as a colonial policeman,
where he'd first grown to

02:25.179 --> 02:26.546
despise the apparatus of a

02:26.547 --> 02:28.348
security state, became more

02:28.349 --> 02:32.084
Orwellian than even he
could have imagined,

02:32.085 --> 02:34.587
a nation where even
having an opinion

02:34.588 --> 02:36.190
could be dangerous.

02:42.730 --> 02:46.599
I am very honored to be here at

02:46.600 --> 02:49.636
this university and to
be the first President

02:49.637 --> 02:51.271
of the United States of America

02:51.272 --> 02:52.705
to visit your country.

02:52.706 --> 02:54.541
Morning in Yangon.

02:54.542 --> 02:56.443
To nearly everyone's surprise,

02:56.444 --> 02:59.045
there have been some huge
changes in recent months.

02:59.046 --> 02:59.980
The most difficult time

02:59.981 --> 03:01.714
in any transition is when we

03:01.715 --> 03:04.584
think that success is in sight.

03:04.585 --> 03:06.886
Nobel Prize-winning
democracy champion

03:06.887 --> 03:10.056
Aung San Suu Kyi, for
nearly 15 years under house

03:10.057 --> 03:13.393
arrest, was released, and
has now taken an active

03:13.394 --> 03:15.028
role in politics.

03:16.897 --> 03:18.565
Just as the door is opening,

03:18.566 --> 03:19.732
my crew and I are among

03:19.733 --> 03:21.067
the first to record what has

03:21.068 --> 03:25.004
been unseen for decades
by most of the world.

03:25.005 --> 03:26.306
Meanwhile, this Southeast Asian

03:26.307 --> 03:28.641
country of 80 million people

03:28.642 --> 03:31.177
is collectively
holding its breath,

03:31.178 --> 03:33.413
waiting to see what's next.

03:33.414 --> 03:37.217
And will this loosening
of government grip last?

03:44.091 --> 03:45.958
Of course, morning in Yangon

03:45.959 --> 03:48.729
has always been about tea.

03:56.970 --> 03:59.171
It's black, Indian-style tea,

03:59.172 --> 04:00.673
usually with a thick dollop

04:00.674 --> 04:03.444
of sweetened condensed milk.

04:05.012 --> 04:09.382
You want it sweet, less
sweet, very sweet, strong,

04:09.383 --> 04:10.318
less strong?

04:10.319 --> 04:11.784
Everybody's got a preference;

04:11.785 --> 04:14.487
everybody's got a
preferred tea shop

04:14.488 --> 04:17.656
where they know, presumably,
how you like yours.

04:17.658 --> 04:21.127
I said I'm only less
sweet, and a bit strong.

04:21.128 --> 04:23.796
Journalist and
publisher U Thiha Saw.

04:23.797 --> 04:26.198
We meet at the Say
Thai Cha Tea Shop.

04:26.199 --> 04:28.301
Anything could happen
in a tea shop.

04:28.302 --> 04:29.336
This place mean, uh, a lot

04:29.337 --> 04:31.304
of things, not just a place for

04:31.305 --> 04:33.341
breakfast and snacks.

04:35.309 --> 04:38.144
For 50 years of
paranoia and repression,

04:38.145 --> 04:41.180
tea houses were also the
main forum for guarded and

04:41.181 --> 04:44.551
not-so-guarded discussions
of the daily news,

04:44.552 --> 04:46.919
where you tried to piece
together the real stories

04:46.920 --> 04:48.821
behind the ludicrously chopped

04:48.822 --> 04:51.157
and censored newspapers.

04:51.158 --> 04:52.392
Carefully, of course, because

04:52.393 --> 04:54.026
informers and secret policese

04:54.027 --> 04:55.995
were also heavily represented

04:55.996 --> 04:59.366
in these hotbeds of
sedition and discontent.

04:59.367 --> 05:00.500
So, given your profession,

05:00.501 --> 05:01.601
how have you managed to stay out

05:01.602 --> 05:03.503
of prison all of these years?

05:03.504 --> 05:05.338
No. I was there.

05:05.339 --> 05:06.406
Oh, really?

05:06.407 --> 05:07.174
Two times.

05:07.174 --> 05:07.941
Two times.

05:07.942 --> 05:09.509
Once special Burma Police

05:09.510 --> 05:10.177
called me. "Hey U Thiha Saw,

05:10.178 --> 05:12.011
will you please come into office?
We need to talk."

05:12.012 --> 05:12.413
Right.

05:12.414 --> 05:17.083
So I went over there
and the total was...

05:17.084 --> 05:19.720
89 days in the prison.

05:21.889 --> 05:24.190
There was this very serious

05:24.191 --> 05:26.593
control that came with the first

05:26.594 --> 05:27.428
military government.

05:27.428 --> 05:28.228
Right.

05:28.229 --> 05:30.630
Press scrutiny and
registration debacle. So...

05:30.631 --> 05:32.599
Oh, that doesn't sound good.

05:32.600 --> 05:33.866
We need to send in our copies

05:33.867 --> 05:35.902
to that office and then
take a look at everything.

05:35.903 --> 05:36.936
They would say, "Take this out.

05:36.937 --> 05:39.305
Take that out or black
this out," or just,

05:39.306 --> 05:40.707
"Take the whole story out."

05:40.708 --> 05:41.475
Magazines that would come

05:41.476 --> 05:43.776
into the country would
they cut out...

05:43.777 --> 05:45.712
Literally cut out
the-the pieces.

05:45.713 --> 05:46.746
Well, the people under this

05:46.747 --> 05:49.081
kind of tight censorship,
people become more,

05:49.082 --> 05:50.417
I think, creative.

05:50.418 --> 05:51.584
Take a look, careful reading,

05:51.585 --> 05:55.455
there may be something
between the lines, messages.

05:55.456 --> 05:57.590
Right. It was something
you were accused of, uh,

05:57.591 --> 05:59.893
sending these secret messages.

06:05.399 --> 06:07.567
In the back, a cauldron
of salty little fish

06:07.568 --> 06:10.136
bubble over hardwood coals.

06:10.137 --> 06:14.306
Fingers work mountains
of sweet bean,

06:14.307 --> 06:15.242
one of the fillings for

06:15.243 --> 06:18.244
the variety of pastries
that are stuffed, shaped,

06:18.245 --> 06:21.715
and put into an old stone oven.

06:24.985 --> 06:26.953
In another corner, the
heartening slap of

06:26.954 --> 06:29.489
fresh bread, pressed
against the clay wall

06:29.490 --> 06:31.190
of a tandoori.

06:31.191 --> 06:33.159
And, of course, eggs
bob and spit in the

06:33.160 --> 06:37.029
magical hell broth of
fish, spice, and herb.

06:37.030 --> 06:37.598
Mohinga?

06:37.599 --> 06:38.765
Uh, this I must have.

06:38.766 --> 06:39.766
Correct me if I'm wrong,

06:39.767 --> 06:41.834
if there's a national
dish, a fundamental,

06:41.835 --> 06:44.437
most beloved dish, would
it be... would it be this?

06:44.438 --> 06:46.372
Yeah, for example, take a
look at all this sweet

06:46.373 --> 06:46.774
stuff.

06:46.775 --> 06:48.107
This is Indian.

06:48.108 --> 06:49.842
These are Chinese, et cetera.

06:49.843 --> 06:52.512
But then mohinga
is a local thing.

06:52.513 --> 06:53.613
And it's popular not in the city

06:53.614 --> 06:54.781
but also in the rural areas,

06:54.782 --> 06:58.718
too, in a fish base with
some rice or noodles.

06:58.719 --> 07:01.454
We would sometimes we
put in some crispies,

07:01.455 --> 07:04.156
like fried beans or...
fried guts.

07:04.157 --> 07:04.825
Mm.

07:04.826 --> 07:06.292
So, these are some
coriander leaves.

07:06.293 --> 07:06.994
Yeah.

07:06.995 --> 07:08.127
You can mix some-some limes.

07:08.128 --> 07:12.265
Sprinkle some in here.

07:12.500 --> 07:14.701
Mm. Good textures.

07:14.702 --> 07:17.136
Particularly in the light of,

07:17.137 --> 07:18.671
uh, Obama's recent visit,

07:18.672 --> 07:21.373
these are interesting times.

07:21.374 --> 07:22.642
Significant changes for the

07:22.643 --> 07:24.711
first time in, you
know, 50 years.

07:24.712 --> 07:25.646
Yeah.

07:25.647 --> 07:27.580
There's one thing which
is quite significant.

07:27.581 --> 07:28.215
For example, take a look around.

07:28.216 --> 07:30.850
All kinds of people,
all age groups.

07:30.851 --> 07:32.151
But a couple of years ago,

07:32.152 --> 07:33.586
people would be... when you're

07:33.587 --> 07:37.389
talking about politics,
you... you tone down.

07:37.390 --> 07:37.658
Right.

07:37.659 --> 07:38.991
I mean, you would be whispering.

07:38.992 --> 07:39.760
But nowadays, people just being

07:39.761 --> 07:41.994
more... are being, uh, outspoken.

07:41.995 --> 07:44.196
So, this has all
become much more open.

07:44.197 --> 07:45.364
In last July, they're sort of

07:45.365 --> 07:47.534
relaxing the rules
about censorship.

07:47.535 --> 07:49.001
August 20th, we were called

07:49.002 --> 07:50.069
into the Unintel office,

07:50.070 --> 07:52.271
we being publishers, editors.

07:52.272 --> 07:53.506
And the director general of

07:53.507 --> 07:55.074
the department said, the boss,

07:55.075 --> 07:58.911
"Okay, 48 years and 20 days
of censorship is gone.

07:58.912 --> 08:00.179
That's it."

08:00.180 --> 08:02.615
Feel good?

08:02.616 --> 08:04.016
Yeah. That's what we've been

08:04.017 --> 08:05.417
waiting for so many years.

08:05.418 --> 08:06.353
I love the-the-the answer.

08:06.354 --> 08:08.521
It's a careful yes.

08:08.522 --> 08:10.356
Yeah. First, people within

08:10.357 --> 08:12.792
the country, we have
some doubt about,

08:12.793 --> 08:15.595
"Okay, is it real, the
changes and the reforms?"

08:15.596 --> 08:17.463
But, as now it's about a couple

08:17.464 --> 08:20.232
of years, and then now
people start believing that,

08:20.233 --> 08:21.901
"Oh, maybe, maybe it's real."

08:21.902 --> 08:24.036
The process is still very young.

08:24.037 --> 08:25.572
It is still possible when the

08:25.573 --> 08:26.906
generals stop and think, "Okay,

08:26.907 --> 08:27.940
that's enough is enough.

08:27.941 --> 08:29.041
Let's turn back all our stuff

08:29.042 --> 08:31.711
"I'm optimistic about the
changes and the reforms.

08:31.712 --> 08:34.514
But I'm still
cautiously optimistic.

08:41.054 --> 08:43.222
In Yangon, motorbikes
are outlawed.

08:43.222 --> 08:46.058
Why is a matter of much
rumor and speculation.

08:46.059 --> 08:48.361
So, it's the bus for me.

08:51.498 --> 08:54.702
Something seems
almost out of sync.

09:00.574 --> 09:03.643
Not too long ago, even
filming here officially

09:03.644 --> 09:06.245
as an open, professional
Western film crew

09:06.246 --> 09:08.148
would have been unthinkable.

09:10.751 --> 09:12.785
In 2007, a Japanese journalist

09:12.786 --> 09:14.453
was shot point-blank and killed

09:14.454 --> 09:17.089
filming a street demonstration.

09:17.090 --> 09:18.424
Be seen talking to anybody with

09:18.425 --> 09:19.592
a camera and there would likely

09:19.593 --> 09:22.596
be a knock on your door in
the middle of the night.

09:24.097 --> 09:26.098
Yet so far, confronted
with our cameras,

09:26.099 --> 09:30.002
a few smiles, and mostly
indifference at worst,

09:30.003 --> 09:32.171
shocking considering how
recently the government

09:32.172 --> 09:34.574
has started to relax its grip.

09:38.846 --> 09:39.946
We love to eat.

09:39.947 --> 09:41.948
And don't forget, for 50
years, we were under two

09:41.949 --> 09:44.116
dictatorships, and
especially under some

09:44.117 --> 09:46.886
socialists, you have not
a lot of things to do.

09:46.887 --> 09:50.489
But, you know, cook and
share food and... you know.

09:50.490 --> 09:52.659
This is Ma Thengi, a famous

09:52.660 --> 09:56.663
and very controversial
figure in public life.

09:56.664 --> 09:58.564
Myanmar or Burma?

09:58.565 --> 09:59.799
Myanmar, because that's

09:59.800 --> 10:04.503
original name since
the, uh, 13th century.

10:04.504 --> 10:06.572
Ma Thengi, like U Thiha Saw,

10:06.573 --> 10:08.741
has also spent time in prison.

10:08.742 --> 10:09.976
But on emerging after three

10:09.977 --> 10:11.477
years, she became in the minds

10:11.478 --> 10:14.881
of many an apologist
for the regime.

10:14.882 --> 10:18.084
Fairly or not, I
leave to others.

10:18.085 --> 10:20.219
Sometimes, outsiders, um, act

10:20.220 --> 10:22.321
as if, you know, it's only after

10:22.322 --> 10:23.923
the military junta went away

10:23.924 --> 10:25.892
that, you know, things happened.

10:25.893 --> 10:27.159
First we were sort of, like, in

10:27.160 --> 10:30.162
a fro... frozen state,
like Snow White.

10:30.163 --> 10:31.898
Dead.

10:31.899 --> 10:34.500
But her many well-known
books on the culinary

10:34.501 --> 10:36.202
traditions of Myanmar

10:36.203 --> 10:39.872
make her a compelling
advocate for Burmese cuisine.

10:39.873 --> 10:42.174
So you're very passionate
about the cooking

10:42.175 --> 10:43.509
and the cuisine here, and...

10:43.510 --> 10:44.844
Well, it's just that I like

10:44.845 --> 10:46.680
to eat and I eat like a pig.

10:48.515 --> 10:51.484
This is Yangon's
field restaurant.

10:53.220 --> 10:56.188
Salads, I think, are
the... the best of our food.

10:56.189 --> 10:57.456
I'm going to order a lot of

10:57.457 --> 10:58.758
salads that you haven't had.

10:58.759 --> 10:59.792
You know, it's going to be like

10:59.793 --> 11:01.060
a sort of a tasting thing.

11:01.061 --> 11:03.796
There's pic head salad
with kaffir lime leaf,

11:03.797 --> 11:06.766
long bean salad with
sesame and fish sauce,

11:06.767 --> 11:09.301
penny leaf salad,
even this salad of

11:09.302 --> 11:10.903
India-style samosa.

11:10.904 --> 11:12.004
Everything's out there
at the same time.

11:12.005 --> 11:12.639
Yes.

11:12.640 --> 11:13.973
No first course, second course.

11:13.974 --> 11:14.641
No, no, no, no.

11:14.642 --> 11:16.308
If I'm invited to a friend's

11:16.309 --> 11:18.778
house, the table would
be covered with dishes.

11:18.779 --> 11:19.212
Right.

11:19.212 --> 11:19.646
Covered.

11:19.647 --> 11:20.880
And it's really about the

11:20.881 --> 11:23.716
interaction between a lot
of colors, textures,

11:23.717 --> 11:24.284
and flavors in one dish.

11:24.284 --> 11:25.252
Yes. Yeah.

11:25.253 --> 11:26.786
Or... Different.

11:26.787 --> 11:27.654
Different.

11:27.655 --> 11:28.721
Yeah.

11:28.722 --> 11:29.389
Wow, I'm in love.

11:29.389 --> 11:29.723
That's good.

11:29.724 --> 11:32.725
Yes. It is.

11:32.726 --> 11:34.761
And of course there's
the maddeningly

11:34.762 --> 11:37.129
delicious condiments and
pickles with which to make

11:37.130 --> 11:38.731
each dish your own.

11:38.732 --> 11:41.000
You make a lot of different
combinations with each

11:41.001 --> 11:41.802
mouthful.

11:41.803 --> 11:43.235
Ah. And this is something

11:43.236 --> 11:44.570
very confusing in general in

11:44.571 --> 11:45.905
this part of the world.

11:45.906 --> 11:47.740
Everybody eats everything
differently, to-

11:47.741 --> 11:49.075
to very much to their taste.

11:49.076 --> 11:49.910
Anything goes.

11:49.910 --> 11:50.577
Anything goes.

11:50.578 --> 11:51.744
You make-every mouthful you

11:51.745 --> 11:54.414
can make as different
as you want.

12:11.264 --> 12:14.935
Credit cards accepted
almost nowhere.

12:16.103 --> 12:17.937
Cash machines, uh-uh.

12:17.938 --> 12:19.638
Wi-Fi? Internet?

12:19.639 --> 12:20.807
Rare.

12:20.808 --> 12:22.775
3G? You got to be kidding.

12:22.776 --> 12:25.277
If you need to exchange
money here, only crisp,

12:25.278 --> 12:28.714
absolutely new $100
bills accepted.

12:28.715 --> 12:32.419
In Myanmar, it's
another, older world.

12:42.295 --> 12:44.130
Oh, and what's up with this?

12:44.131 --> 12:47.499
With all the, uh, kissing
sounds, that smooching,

12:47.500 --> 12:48.335
kissing, you know,
sound that you're

12:48.336 --> 12:50.136
hearing all over the place?

12:50.137 --> 12:52.872
My wife would have been in,
like, 10 fights so far.

12:52.873 --> 12:56.008
Sorry? Who... who are
you smooching at?

12:56.009 --> 12:57.243
Bitch?

12:57.244 --> 12:59.345
This is how you summon a waiter

12:59.346 --> 13:01.480
in Myanmar. I know. I know.

13:01.481 --> 13:02.849
Try that at Hooters and you

13:02.850 --> 13:04.650
will be rightly ejected.

13:04.651 --> 13:07.020
It takes some getting
used to, for sure.

13:08.055 --> 13:11.023
Min lane is a big, noisy
seafood house where fish

13:11.024 --> 13:13.525
is prepared in the
style of Rhakine,

13:13.526 --> 13:14.726
the coastal province to the

13:14.727 --> 13:19.098
west named for the Rhakine
people, one of over 135

13:19.099 --> 13:21.367
distinct ethnic
groups around here.

13:21.368 --> 13:23.870
See, now we're talking Prawn
curry is one of those-

13:23.871 --> 13:24.737
one of those things everybody

13:24.738 --> 13:26.372
tells you you got to eat here.

13:26.373 --> 13:30.109
Prawns from the river,
in tomato curry.

13:30.110 --> 13:32.778
I tell you this, good sauce.

13:32.779 --> 13:34.113
Oh, that's good.

13:34.114 --> 13:36.348
That is some good
shit, my friends.

13:36.349 --> 13:39.920
We shall know them by the
number of their dead.

13:46.894 --> 13:48.727
Early morning in Yangon.

13:48.728 --> 13:50.262
Among the crush of commuters,

13:50.263 --> 13:54.533
shoppers, people trying
to make a living,

13:54.534 --> 13:57.870
rise up the last remnants
of empire, faded,

13:57.871 --> 13:59.906
often crumbling, but still there

13:59.907 --> 14:01.740
after all these years.

14:01.741 --> 14:03.943
These are the
offices, businesses,

14:03.944 --> 14:07.447
and public buildings of
the British colonials.

14:17.124 --> 14:18.324
The Sofaer building was once

14:18.325 --> 14:22.295
one of the swankest
department stores in Rangoon.

14:25.899 --> 14:26.999
A century ago, when Kipling's

14:27.000 --> 14:28.800
poem "Mandalay" was beckoning

14:28.801 --> 14:30.436
the overheated imaginations of

14:30.437 --> 14:31.570
a generation of young

14:31.571 --> 14:33.339
Englishmen, here you could buy

14:33.340 --> 14:36.943
fine Egyptian cigarettes,
French liqueurs.

14:36.944 --> 14:40.779
The floor tiles were shipped
over from Manchester.

14:40.780 --> 14:43.282
Now, people live here.

14:43.283 --> 14:44.750
A half-century as a pariah

14:44.751 --> 14:46.085
state has left very few of

14:46.086 --> 14:48.587
these buildings in good repair.

14:48.588 --> 14:50.089
And there are divergent views

14:50.090 --> 14:51.690
on whether to preserve them.

14:51.691 --> 14:54.961
For many, a reminder of
colonial subjugation.

14:54.962 --> 14:58.831
For others, a vestige
of a golden time.

15:07.274 --> 15:08.141
These days in Myanmar in the

15:08.142 --> 15:10.709
streets, on the docks, it's all

15:10.710 --> 15:12.211
