is thanaka, a face paint
and sunblock made

29:47.519 --> 29:51.923
from tree bark that masks
many of their faces.

29:51.924 --> 29:53.324
It's ubiquitous here.

29:53.325 --> 29:54.926
At first jarring to see,

29:54.927 --> 29:56.394
it quickly becomes something

29:56.395 --> 29:59.731
you get used to and
take for granted.

30:17.884 --> 30:20.285
Yangon's gravitational
pull broken,

30:20.286 --> 30:21.552
and with darkness falling,

30:21.553 --> 30:23.189
the train picks up speed.

30:26.558 --> 30:29.361
At times, terrifyingly so.

30:33.765 --> 30:34.966
I mean, this thing is going

30:34.967 --> 30:37.569
to derail at some point.

30:39.538 --> 30:40.771
They have lost how many wheels

30:40.772 --> 30:43.808
yesterday on this one train?

30:43.809 --> 30:46.811
So, truly, it's about
being in the right car,

30:46.812 --> 30:49.314
the one that keeps its wheel.

30:49.315 --> 30:51.482
Derailments, or "rail slips,"

30:51.483 --> 30:52.817
as they are referred to here,

30:52.818 --> 30:54.319
a somewhat more benign-sounding

30:54.320 --> 30:56.654
occurrence than, say,
"Rolling off the tracks into

30:56.655 --> 30:57.989
a rice paddy,"

30:57.990 --> 31:00.126
are not uncommon.

31:04.096 --> 31:05.730
And one can't help wondering

31:05.731 --> 31:07.132
what the engineer and conductor

31:07.133 --> 31:08.633
are thinking as the trainductor

31:08.634 --> 31:13.139
speeds heedlessly on,
faster and faster.

31:13.805 --> 31:16.674
I mean, it must be, what,
about 40, 50 miles per

31:16.675 --> 31:17.909
hour at this point.

31:17.910 --> 31:18.677
I wonder if anyone has ever,

31:18.677 --> 31:19.578
like, flown right out of their

31:19.579 --> 31:21.279
seat, out the window.

31:21.280 --> 31:24.182
Yes, small people, sure.

31:24.183 --> 31:26.918
You don't want to be,
like, holding a lap dog.

31:26.919 --> 31:28.353
Or a baby, or anything.

31:28.354 --> 31:30.688
I mean, it's...
Try pissing in the

31:30.689 --> 31:33.358
bathroom and find yourself
launched straight up

31:33.359 --> 31:35.760
into the ceiling, bringing
to a rude conclusion

31:35.761 --> 31:40.566
what was already an
omnidirectional experience.

31:44.103 --> 31:45.203
It's smooth now.

31:45.204 --> 31:47.239
It's very relaxing.

31:48.274 --> 31:50.675
What kind of beer did he have?

31:50.676 --> 31:52.344
I want the same.

32:28.880 --> 32:29.648
Samosa?

32:29.648 --> 32:30.482
Yes.

32:30.483 --> 32:31.749
Yeah.

32:31.750 --> 32:33.718
1,000?

32:33.719 --> 32:35.320
Done.

32:35.321 --> 32:39.090
Now, this is breakfast.

32:39.091 --> 32:41.926
Nearly 19 hours
into our 10-hour trip,

32:41.927 --> 32:43.428
and the night express to Bagan

32:43.429 --> 32:45.696
lurches and bounces onward over

32:45.697 --> 32:49.434
old and poorly
maintained tracks.

32:49.435 --> 32:52.370
Could have flown back to
New York for breakfast.

32:52.371 --> 32:53.771
I-I had time.

32:53.772 --> 32:57.042
What's in yours? Carrots.

32:57.043 --> 32:59.677
Root. I got potatoes in mine.

32:59.678 --> 33:01.346
How to make good food pretty.

33:01.347 --> 33:02.380
Look at this.

33:02.381 --> 33:03.848
A bouquet of fish.

33:03.849 --> 33:05.884
Indeed.

33:11.457 --> 33:12.424
So, this is it.

33:12.425 --> 33:15.361
This is the Plain of Bagan.

33:20.266 --> 33:21.632
Out the window, the modern

33:21.633 --> 33:23.301
world seems to fade away, ern

33:23.302 --> 33:25.703
then disappear altogether,

33:25.704 --> 33:27.072
like the last century never

33:27.073 --> 33:31.410
happened, or even the
century before that.

33:33.212 --> 33:34.046
We're traveling across the

33:34.047 --> 33:39.117
largest mainland nation
in Southeast Asia.

33:39.118 --> 33:40.418
But it should be pointed out

33:40.419 --> 33:41.486
that we are still within the

33:41.487 --> 33:44.755
confines of the
tourist triangle,

33:44.756 --> 33:48.426
areas permissible for travel.

33:48.427 --> 33:51.162
Whole sectors of this
country, much of it, in fact,

33:51.163 --> 33:54.999
are off-limits. Simply put,

33:55.000 --> 33:59.804
there is shit going on they
do not want you to see.

33:59.805 --> 34:01.606
A low-intensity conflict with

34:01.607 --> 34:04.442
the ethnic Kachin tribe
would be one of them,

34:04.443 --> 34:09.580
a wave of persecution and
deaths in Rhakine state.

34:09.581 --> 34:11.982
The country may be opening
up at its center,

34:11.983 --> 34:13.518
but all along the edges it's

34:13.518 --> 34:15.520
waging a desperate war to hang

34:15.521 --> 34:18.156
on to the status quo.

34:18.157 --> 34:22.628
Needless to say, the
status quo is not good.

34:29.168 --> 34:31.034
All right.

34:31.036 --> 34:33.772
Bagan, here we come.

34:47.886 --> 34:50.221
1,000 years ago, Bagan
was the capital for a

34:50.222 --> 34:53.791
long line of Bama kings.

34:53.792 --> 34:54.958
It's the sort of place where

34:54.960 --> 34:59.230
the old coexists
with the even older.

34:59.231 --> 35:00.166
As elsewhere in this part of

35:00.167 --> 35:02.833
the world, in many of the
Buddhist temples here,

35:02.834 --> 35:05.203
far older animist spirit-based

35:05.204 --> 35:09.207
beliefs coexist with
more recent Buddhism.

35:09.208 --> 35:11.409
And, in Myanmar,
worship of the Nats

35:11.410 --> 35:13.344
is widespread.

35:13.345 --> 35:16.814
Nats, as I understand it,
are more like Greek gods,

35:16.815 --> 35:18.816
former humans, demigods,

35:18.817 --> 35:20.585
spirits, often with very human

35:20.586 --> 35:22.820
qualities and failings.

35:26.057 --> 35:27.425
Dance performances pay homage

35:27.426 --> 35:29.594
to the individual Nats,

35:29.595 --> 35:31.262
performers claiming to actually

35:31.263 --> 35:32.863
channel them, bringing about,

35:32.864 --> 35:37.736
one hopes, a beneficial
spiritual possession.

35:42.574 --> 35:45.743
But I'm not just
here for a Nat Pwey.

35:45.744 --> 35:46.944
I have a list:

35:46.945 --> 35:49.180
things to eat in Myanmar.

35:49.181 --> 35:50.881
And this is one of them.

35:50.882 --> 35:53.284
Chicken curry.

35:53.285 --> 35:55.286
And from roadside
joints like this,

35:55.287 --> 35:56.954
nestled among the temple ruins,

35:56.955 --> 35:57.889
you're more than likely touins,

35:57.890 --> 36:02.293
catch a very enticing whiff.

36:02.294 --> 36:03.594
Just delicious.

36:03.595 --> 36:05.463
Spicy, but not to the point
that you want to scream

36:05.464 --> 36:09.133
out for mercy, but some heat.

36:09.134 --> 36:10.134
Slow simmered curry,

36:10.135 --> 36:12.036
served with a side of sour soup

36:12.037 --> 36:14.372
made from roselle leaves.

36:14.373 --> 36:16.307
With it, you get
fried, ground chilies,

36:16.308 --> 36:19.109
pickled bean sprouts...
You get the idea.

36:19.110 --> 36:20.945
They always have,
like, these relishes,

36:20.946 --> 36:22.247
these dippy type things, these,

36:22.248 --> 36:24.549
like, really interesting
salads, and I'm, like,

36:24.550 --> 36:26.551
not really a salad guy.

36:26.552 --> 36:29.554
The salads here are,
uh... they're happening.

36:29.555 --> 36:32.457
Spicy, sour, salty,
savory, just delicious.

36:32.458 --> 36:33.225
It's delicious.

36:33.226 --> 36:35.826
A plethora of
textures and flavors.

36:35.827 --> 36:36.827
This is a culture that's

36:36.828 --> 36:38.095
thought a lot about their food,

36:38.096 --> 36:41.666
clearly like eating,
like feeding people.

36:41.667 --> 36:42.667
They think a lot about those

36:42.668 --> 36:48.673
classic balances of flavors,
colors, and textures.

36:48.674 --> 36:51.477
Best restaurant in the
country so far, by the way.

37:14.700 --> 37:16.501
You'd expect this, an ancient

37:16.502 --> 37:19.670
city of nearly unparalleled
size and beauty,

37:19.671 --> 37:21.372
to be overrun with tourists,

37:21.373 --> 37:25.343
souvenir shops, snack
bars, tours on tape...

37:25.344 --> 37:26.344
But no.

37:26.345 --> 37:29.448
Oh, this is stunning.

37:29.881 --> 37:31.649
You'll encounter some
Western travelers at

37:31.650 --> 37:33.318
Bagan's temple sites for sure,

37:33.319 --> 37:36.554
but, generally speaking,
they're a hardy bunch...

37:36.555 --> 37:37.888
Even the bus tours here are not

37:37.889 --> 37:41.627
for the faint of heart
or the weak of spirit.

37:42.027 --> 37:43.027
But for the most part,

37:43.028 --> 37:44.228
you're far more likely to bump

37:44.229 --> 37:47.031
into a goat than a foreigner.

37:47.032 --> 37:52.737
This is so beautiful, so
much like an ode to human,

37:52.738 --> 37:54.639
you know, beliefs and adoration

37:54.640 --> 37:58.075
and worshiping
and-and... Slave labor.

37:58.076 --> 37:59.477
And slave labor.

37:59.478 --> 38:01.679
I'm thinking, you build
this many temples,

38:01.680 --> 38:04.081
thousands of them, in
a relatively short

38:04.082 --> 38:04.883
period of time?

38:04.884 --> 38:05.884
You know, chances are somebody

38:05.885 --> 38:07.552
was working for less
than minimum wage,

38:07.553 --> 38:08.653
let's put it that way.

38:08.654 --> 38:10.254
For sure.

38:10.255 --> 38:13.658
Ah, we could fly here.

38:13.659 --> 38:14.892
Look at that.

38:14.893 --> 38:18.229
Whew.

38:23.402 --> 38:26.236
A millennia ago, in
a period of just under

38:26.237 --> 38:30.274
250 years, over 4,000
structures like this

38:30.275 --> 38:32.478
were built here.

38:33.712 --> 38:34.879
They say that a Bama king,

38:34.880 --> 38:37.882
Anorata, began this project
after a conversion to

38:37.883 --> 38:41.820
Theravada-style Buddhism.

38:43.088 --> 38:46.425
They started a new temple,
like, every 14 days.

38:48.627 --> 38:52.096
Over 3,000 pagodas,
temples, and monasteries

38:52.097 --> 38:53.631
remain today.

38:53.632 --> 38:57.067
Inside almost every one
of them, a Buddha figure,

38:57.068 --> 38:59.804
each one different.

38:59.805 --> 39:02.440
And I like how integrated
it is with those

39:02.441 --> 39:04.775
trees, ox trails, and...

39:04.776 --> 39:06.477
Actually, funny you
should mention that.

39:06.478 --> 39:08.813
People used to live here,
but the government came

39:08.814 --> 39:10.781
along in the '80s, I believe,

39:10.782 --> 39:13.283
and relocated... it was a
mass relocation project.

39:13.284 --> 39:13.952
Right.

39:13.953 --> 39:15.920
So, any homes, anything, it

39:15.921 --> 39:18.122
was understood that this
is a good... you know,

39:18.123 --> 39:19.289
there's some tourist bucks here.

39:19.290 --> 39:22.394
They relocated the
entire population.

39:26.965 --> 39:30.501
We're in one of the first
mass waves of tourists.

39:30.502 --> 39:31.769
European tourists have been

39:31.770 --> 39:33.103
coming here in relatively small

39:33.104 --> 39:34.072
numbers for a long time.

39:34.073 --> 39:36.106
But the floodgates
have certainly opened.

39:36.107 --> 39:37.141
They're building hotels like

39:37.142 --> 39:40.144
crazy around this area,
what's called the

39:40.145 --> 39:41.145
Tourist Triangle.

39:41.146 --> 39:42.647
I really like this, too.

39:42.648 --> 39:44.982
This is silk and cotton poly.

39:44.983 --> 39:46.984
And what-what is this here?
Oh, this-this is a...

39:46.985 --> 39:49.454
This is a nice cloth.

39:49.455 --> 39:50.488
As Myanmar begins

39:50.489 --> 39:52.156
its shift towards accommodating

39:52.157 --> 39:53.591
increasing tourism and a

39:53.592 --> 39:55.526
service economy to go with it,

39:55.527 --> 39:57.862
there will be adjustments.

39:57.863 --> 40:00.531
There will be, of
course, a downside.

40:00.532 --> 40:02.433
Now, how much you pay?

40:02.434 --> 40:03.168
Okay.

40:03.169 --> 40:05.369
What's that going to mean?
How will the Burmese

40:05.370 --> 40:07.638
react to all of the goods-good

40:07.639 --> 40:10.007
and evils that
come with tourism?

40:10.008 --> 40:10.842
Okay, Mister.

40:10.843 --> 40:12.677
What about... you pay one. Okay.

40:12.678 --> 40:13.445
Perfect. It's perfect, yeah.

40:13.445 --> 40:14.045
Excuse me.

40:14.046 --> 40:15.646
It's going to mean mobility.

40:15.647 --> 40:17.682
It's going to mean
prosperity for some.

40:17.683 --> 40:19.484
Will mean a lot of bad
things, too, you know.

40:19.485 --> 40:20.685
It'll mean prostitution;

40:20.686 --> 40:22.119
it'll mean hustling.

40:22.120 --> 40:23.153
Here you go. Okay, my booth

40:23.154 --> 40:24.154
Unintel fine restaurant.

40:25.824 --> 40:27.157
Okay. And you, too.

40:27.158 --> 40:27.993
Everybody is selling to you,

40:27.994 --> 40:30.828
you buy Unintel, you
pay 20, you buy...

40:30.829 --> 40:31.730
I know, I know.

40:31.731 --> 40:32.797
But you don't buy postcard.

40:32.798 --> 40:33.665
Now, that's no fair.

40:33.665 --> 40:34.566
You buy postcard, also fair.

40:34.567 --> 40:35.900
But I don't need the postcard.

40:35.901 --> 40:37.334
We're told that
kids are dropping out

40:37.335 --> 40:40.004
of school to do this, the
double-edged sword of

40:40.005 --> 40:41.371
the service economy.

40:41.372 --> 40:42.540
You want to buy postcard?

40:42.541 --> 40:43.974
For, uh, only $5.

40:43.975 --> 40:45.476
One, two, three, more, five,

40:45.477 --> 40:47.112
six, seven, eight, nine, 10.

40:54.019 --> 40:55.486
What I'm amazed is how
friendly and open people

40:55.487 --> 40:56.187
are with us.

40:56.188 --> 40:58.055
It's very easy for me to sit

40:58.056 --> 41:00.858
here and say whatever I
want about the government.

41:00.859 --> 41:01.493
Right?

41:01.494 --> 41:03.193
We can go home.

41:03.194 --> 41:04.162
You know.

41:04.163 --> 41:06.565
Our lives will go on.

41:08.333 --> 41:11.836
We don't pay the
price for that show.

41:11.837 --> 41:14.404
Uh, everybody who helped us

41:14.405 --> 41:16.841
could very well pay that price.

41:16.842 --> 41:17.875
It should be pointed out that a

41:17.876 --> 41:19.510
lot of people did not.

41:19.511 --> 41:21.278
A lot of people were very
nice to us but said,

41:21.279 --> 41:24.248
"Look, I just... I've
already been in jail."

41:24.249 --> 41:26.250
You know?" I don't... I
really don't want to

41:26.251 --> 41:27.417
go back."

41:27.418 --> 41:29.219
Um, it's a very real concern.

41:29.220 --> 41:31.188
What happens to the
people we leave behind?

41:31.189 --> 41:32.023
You know, one would think that

41:32.024 --> 41:34.592
you can't... once freedom...
You know, they've tasted

41:34.593 --> 41:35.293
freedom, you know?

41:35.294 --> 41:40.230
Well, uh, uh, you know, you
can put the toothpaste

41:40.231 --> 41:41.365
back in the tube.

41:41.366 --> 41:41.933
You know?

41:41.934 --> 41:44.603
Uh, there's no doubt about that.

41:45.637 --> 41:47.137
But for the moment at least,

41:47.138 --> 41:50.474
things seem to be moving
in the right direction.

41:50.475 --> 41:53.578
A country closed off
to most for so long,

41:53.579 --> 41:55.813
sleeping, a 50-year
nightmare for

41:55.814 --> 42:00.450
many of its citizens,
finally may be waking up.

42:00.451 --> 42:01.586
To what?

42:01.587 --> 42:03.521
Time will tell.

